Assignment 1 ¶

This assignment covers some basics of graph theory and traditonal graph analysis approaches with NetworkX package, including the implementation of defining undirected and directed graphs, homogeneous graph vs. heterogenous graph, comppute their adjacency matrix- $A$, degree matrix - $D$, and laplacian matrix - $L$.

The primary objective of this assignment is to deepen your understanding of traditional graph analysis methods (e.g., node level statistics and graph kenel methods for measuring graph similarity) and basic graph operations using NetworkX and Grakel package. Additionally, you will become more acquainted with implementing graph analytics using python, specifically for the task of graph similarity comparisons.

Reference:

  • Tutorial on the NetworkX library: https://networkx.org/documentation/stable/tutorial.html
  • Grakel package for graph kenel implementations: https://ysig.github.io/GraKeL/0.1a8/graph_kernel.html

Note: You must run/evaluate all cells. Order of cell execution is important.

Other reference: https://chatgpt.com/share/68d7a2e5-7500-8013-a6b0-e732f2bdaa77

1. Basic graph definition and matrix representation (11pts)¶

In [9]:
import networkx as nx
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import random
import numpy as np

seed = 33

random.seed(seed)


####################################
'''1. Undirected Graph'''
####################################

# Define a random undirected graph ($G_u$) with 30 nodes (1pt)
# (Please make the graph reproducible via set a fixed random seed)
# Using the Erdos-Rényi model for undirected generation (each edge has probability p of being created)

n = 30   # number of nodes
p = 0.1  # probability of edge creation

G = nx.gnp_random_graph(n,p,seed=seed)

# Draw the graph (1pt)
nx.draw(G, with_labels=True, node_color='red', edge_color='darkblue')
plt.title('1. Undirected Graph', loc="left")
plt.show()
# Compute and visualize the A, D, and L matrices for G_u (3pts)
A = nx.adjacency_matrix(G)
print("\nAdjacency Matrix for undirected graph: \n",A.todense())

degrees = G.degree()
D = np.diag([degrees[node] for node in G.nodes()])
print("\nDegree Matrix for undirected graph: \n",D)

L = nx.laplacian_matrix(G)
print("\nLaplacian Matrix for undirected graph: \n", L.todense())

L1 = D - A
flag = 0
for i in range(L1.shape[0]):
  for j in range(L1.shape[1]):
    if L1[i,j] != L[i,j]:
      flag = 1

status = '\nLaplacians for undirected match.' if flag==0 else '\nThis cannot be happening.'
print(status)

####################################
'''2. Directed Graph'''
####################################

# Define a directed graph (G_d)  with 30 nodes  (1pt)
G_d = nx.gnp_random_graph(n,p,seed=seed,directed=True)


# Compute and visualize the A, D_in, D_out,  L_in, and L_out matrices for G_d (5pts)
A_d = nx.adjacency_matrix(G_d)
print("\nAdjacency Matrix for directed graph: \n",A_d.todense())

in_degrees = G_d.in_degree()
print(type(in_degrees))
in_degrees = dict(in_degrees)
D_in = np.diag([in_degrees[node] for node in in_degrees.keys()])
print("\nIn-Degree Matrix for directed graph: \n",D_in)

out_degrees = G_d.out_degree()
out_degrees = dict(out_degrees)
D_out = np.diag([out_degrees[node] for node in out_degrees.keys()])
print("\nOut-Degree Matrix for directed graph: \n",D_out)

L_in = D_in - A_d
print("\nIn-Laplacian Matrix for directed graph: \n", L_in)

r = len(L_in)
c = len(L_in[0])

all_zero = True

for j in range(c):
  colSum = 0
  for i in range(r):
    colSum += L_in[i][j]
  if colSum != 0:
    all_zero = False

status = '\n L_in is fine.' if all_zero else '\nThis cannot be happening.'
print(status)

L_out = D_out - A_d
print("\nOut-Laplacian Matrix for directed graph: \n", L_out)

r = len(L_out)
c = len(L_out[0])

all_zero = True

for i in range(r):
  rowSum = 0
  for j in range(c):
    rowSum += L_out[i][j]
  if rowSum != 0:
    all_zero = False

status = '\n L_out is fine.' if all_zero else '\nThis cannot be happening.'
print(status)

# For each centrality measure, print the top three nodes along with their corresponding centrality values. (6pts)
def printTopThree(name, centrality_dict):
  sorted_dict = dict(sorted(centrality_dict.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))
  top_three = dict(list(sorted_dict.items())[:3])
  print("Top 3 nodes by ",name)
  for node, val in top_three.items():
    print(node, round(val,2))

printTopThree("Degree Centrality", C_d)
print("\n")
printTopThree("Eigenvector Centrality", C_e)
print("\n")
printTopThree("Betweenness Centrality", C_b)
print("\n")
printTopThree("Closeness Centrality", C_c)


# Check whether the created barabasi-albert graph follows a power-law distribution. (2pts)

'''
A power law distribution is a statistical relationship where one quantity varies as a constant power of another,
commonly expressed as y = ax^k, meaning that small events are frequent while large events are rare but can be
significantly more extreme than in a normal distribution. This "scale-free" distribution is characterized by a
"fat tail," allowing for extremely large outcomes, unlike the "thin tail" of a normal (bell curve) distribution.
It is defined by the size (by def. degree) of the nodes in the graph.
'''

deg = [d for _, d in G_ba.degree()]

# Count nodes for each degree
unique_deg, counts = np.unique(deg, return_counts=True)

# Plot degree distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.bar(unique_deg, counts, width=0.80, color="steelblue")

plt.xlabel("Degree k")
plt.ylabel("Number of nodes with degree k")
plt.title("Degree Distribution of BA Graph")
plt.grid(True, which="both", ls="--", alpha=0.4)

# Create a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
import networkx as nx
import pandas as pd

# Create a directed acyclic graph. (DAG)
DAG = nx.gn_graph(15, seed=33)

# Compute Katz centrality for DAG. (2pts)
A = nx.adjacency_matrix(DAG).todense()

eigenValues = np.linalg.eigvals(A)
print("All eigenvalues are ",eigenValues)
largestLambda = max(abs(eigenValues))
print(f"Largest eigen value of DAG's adjacency matrix is {largestLambda:.2f}")

'''
A of DAG's is always nilpotent.
Since largestLambda is 0, 1/largestLambda will be tending to infinity. We can take any integer for alpha.
'''
# using default value of 0.1 for alpha and 1 for beta with 1000 iterations.
kc = nx.katz_centrality_numpy(DAG)

Explanation for hub and authority scores in HITS.¶

  • A node is a strong hub if it points to strong authority nodes, which is visible in the graph as nodes 14, 12, 11 and 10 point directly to the strong authority node 5. These nodes channel the influence towards node 5. The hubs reinforce the centrality and importance of node 5 by serving as distributors or sources of information.
  • A node has a strong authority if it pointed to by many strong hubs. In graph, clearly 5 is the strong authority. Other nodes such as 2 and 1 are pointed to by weaker hubs. The high authority score for 5 also backs the fact it is clearly the endpoint of many directed paths in this DAG. It also indicates that that it is the central connector, serving as the bottleneck and a point of vulnerability. As it is a trusted reference for many hubs, it is vital for aggregating or validating information.
  • If hubs represent influential people, authorities can be considered to be very credible people as they can serve as information validators.

import networkx as nx
import numpy as np
from collections import Counter
from grakel import GraphKernel, Graph
import seaborn as sns

#############################################################################################
''' A. Compare graph similarity based on the Shortest Path Kernel (K_sp) -- 10pts'''
#############################################################################################

# 1. Define four larger, 10-node graphs 🕸️
# G_path: A simple line graph (long and thin)
G_path = nx.path_graph(10)

# G_cycle: A ring graph
G_cycle = nx.cycle_graph(10)

# G_star: A central node connected to 9 others (highly centralized)
# nx.star_graph(n) creates a graph with n+1 nodes.
G_star = nx.star_graph(9)

# G_barbell: Two dense 5-node clusters connected by a single bridge.
# nx.barbell_graph(m1, m2) connects two complete graphs of size m1
# with a path of length m2. m2=0 means they are directly connected.
G_barbell = nx.barbell_graph(5, 0)

graphs = [G_path, G_cycle, G_star, G_barbell]
graph_names = ["G_path", "G_cycle", "G_star", "G_barbell"]

# 2. Visualize the four graphs in one figure of 1*4 subplots. (2pts)
fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 4, figsize=(12, 8))

# 3. Determine the maximum shortest path length across all graphs. (2pts)

# Since these are connected graphs, we can use ax.diameter
maxDiameter = 0.0
for i, graph in enumerate(graphs):
  diameter = nx.diameter(graph)
  print(f"{graph_names[i]}: diameter = {diameter}")
  if diameter > maxDiameter:
    maxDiameter = diameter
print('--------------------------------------------------------------')
print(f"Maximum shortest path length across all graphs: {maxDiameter}")
print('--------------------------------------------------------------')


# 4. Calculate frequency vectors for each graph. (2pts)
freqVectors = []

for graph in graphs:
  # gets a dictionary of shortest path lengths between all pairs of nodes in graph
  shortestPathLengths = dict(nx.all_pairs_shortest_path_length(graph))
  freq = Counter()
  for origin in shortestPathLengths:
    # calculate frequency of each shortest path in graph
    for destination, length in shortestPathLengths[origin].items():
      if origin < destination: # avoid double-counting
        freq[length] +=1
    totalPairs = len(graph) * (len(graph) - 1) // 2
    freq_vector = [freq.get(i, 0) / totalPairs for i in range(maxDiameter + 1)]
  freqVectors.append(freq_vector)

normed_freqVectors = [vec / np.linalg.norm(vec) for vec in freqVectors]

for name, freq in zip(graph_names, normed_freqVectors):
  print(f'{name}\'s frequency vector is {freq}')

# 5. Compute the 4x4 kernel matrix using dot product. (2pts)
kernelMatrix = np.zeros((len(graphs),len(graphs)))

for i in range(len(graphs)):
  for j in range(len(graphs)):
    kernelMatrix[i][j] = np.dot(normed_freqVectors[i], normed_freqVectors[j])


# 6. Visualize the 4x4 kernel matrix using heatmap with labels. (2pts)
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.heatmap(kernelMatrix, annot=True, xticklabels=graph_names, yticklabels=graph_names, cmap="YlOrRd")
plt.title("Shortest Path Kernel Matrix")
plt.show()

# spectral radius and safe lambda were generated using GPT since an initial attempt with default lambda resulted
# in a weird kernel when normalized.

rhos = []
for graph in graphs:
  A = nx.adjacency_matrix(graph).todense()
  # symmetric -> use eigh for stability
  vals = np.linalg.eigvalsh(A)
  rhos.append(np.max(np.abs(vals)))
rho_max = max(rhos)

#a safe lambda
lam = 0.9 / (rho_max**2)
print(f"rho_max={rho_max:.4f}, using lamda={lam:.6g}")

# 1. Convert networkx graphs to GraKeL format (2pts)

Comparisons of Shortest Path and Random Walk kernels¶

  • To begin with, SP compares distributions of shortest path lengths across pairs of nodes in two graphs, thereby a global measure over each graph whereas RW compares based on matching random walks emphasizing local structure such as adjacent sequences.
  • G_path vs G_cycle - K_rw assigns maximum similarity as most nodes have a degree of two and are connected in a chain. But, K_sp assigns a lower similarity of 0.93 since path lengths get diminished in the cycle (its global structure).
  • G_path / G_cycle vs G_star - K_rw similarity score of 0.95 / 0.96 suggests that the structure of the star generates similar walks, most likely due to short ones. However, K_sp assigns a score of 0.59 with both the graphs since the hub-and-spoke structure of the star results in recurring shortest distance of 2 across multile spokes which contracts to the longer lengths observed in path and cycle graphs.
  • G_barbell vs others - K_rw indicates very low similarity (0.49 to 0.61) because random walks tend to get trapped in the local cliques of node 5 and node 4 - a higher similarity with star graph since these walks are short - whereas K_sp has higher measures because of the presense of interclique paths that generate longer distances that are comparable to path and cycles (0.79) and intra-clique shortest paths help align it with star-graph (0.47).
  • Clearly, K_rw tends to over generalize as it blurs the differences between path, cycle and star graphs whereas K_sp provides strong discrimination. To conclude, K_rw should be employed when local patterns are useful and K_sp should be used when large-scale distance structures are crucial.
